.if n .ad l
.nh
.SH "NAME"
MooseX::Role::Listenable \- A parameterized role for observable objects
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 9
\&  # a class with an observable feature\- notifies observers
\&  # when door opened
\&  package Car;
\&  use Moose;
\&  with \*(AqMooseX::Role::Listenable\*(Aq => {event => \*(Aqdoor_opened\*(Aq};
\&  sub open_door {
\&      ... # actually open the door
\&      $self\->door_opened; # notify observers
\&  }
\&
\&  # an observer class that can listen to door_opened events
\&  package Dashboard;
\&  use Moose;
\&  sub door_opened { print "Got door_opened event!\en" }
\&
\&  # attach observer to observable
\&  $car\->add_door_opened_listener($dashboard);
\&
\&  # detach
\&  $car\->remove_door_opened_listener($dashboard);
.Ve
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
A simple implemenation of the observable pattern. By adding this to a class:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&  with \*(AqMooseX::Role::Listenable\*(Aq => {event => \*(Aqsome_event_name\*(Aq};
.Ve
.PP
You are making the class observable for the event 'some_event_name'. You
can call the method \f(CW\*(C`some_event_name()\*(C'\fR on the object, and all listeners
added with \f(CW\*(C`add_some_event_name_listener()\*(C'\fR will be notified. Listeners
will be notified by calling their method \f(CW\*(C`some_event_name()\*(C'\fR.
.PP
Note the list of listeners is a \f(CW\*(C`Set::Object::Weak\*(C'\fR, so be sure to keep
a reference to them somewhere else.
